Tests for the three preflight generators — `probe`, `snippet`, and `claude_invocation` — injected into every `claude` launch to verify the cage environment and prepare context before the LLM runs. Tests exercise these as real shell (not string matching) to verify their actual behavior under `sh -c`.

`probe(label, command)` generates a shell script that runs `command` via `sh -c`, captures combined stdout and stderr, reports the label and output, and exits zero regardless of the command's exit code (fail-open); on nonzero exit it annotates with `NOTE: <label> exited <code>`. `snippet()` generates the full preflight block that runs `ctx-verify` first, then `ctx-context .`, combines their output into `$PREFLIGHT`, echoes it to stdout for the operator, and appends it to `$SYSTEM_PROMPT_FILE`. `claude_invocation(headless)` generates the command line that invokes the Claude binary with `--append-system-prompt-file "$SYSTEM_PROMPT_FILE"` (never both `--append-system-prompt` and `--append-system-prompt-file` together); in headless mode it includes `"$CTX_TASK_BRIEF"` as the task, in interactive mode it uses `setsid --ctty --wait` and omits the task.

All three functions hardcode `/cage/bin/...` absolute paths that exist only inside a real cage; tests verify structure only, not availability. `run_sh` helper spawns real `sh` to capture exit codes and stdout as strings, letting tests assert on actual shell behavior rather than generated syntax.